<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">&#x2022;</font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;">Advanced the pre-clinical development of other compounds from our proprietary series of selective cortisol modulators.</font></p></td></tr></table></div>
<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</p></td>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">&#x2022;</font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;">Began the Phase 1 trial of CORT118335, our proprietary cortisol modulator which has shown promise as a potential treatment for patients with anti-psychotic induced weight gain and non-alcoholic steatohepatitis.</font></p></td></tr></table></div>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Executive Compensation 2017 Program Overview</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Based on our compensation principles and in light of both company and individual performance, the Compensation Committee took the following actions with respect to the compensation for our named executive officers for 2017:</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Salary.<font style="font-style:normal;"> Effective March 1, 2017, the Compensation Committee approved 5.5 percent increases to the annual base salaries of Dr. Belanoff, Mr. Robb, Mr. Maduck and Mr. Fishman.</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Bonuses<font style="font-style:normal;">.&#160;In accordance with our practice of awarding bonuses to named executive officers for the achievement of significant corporate goals, in February 2018, we paid bonuses to all employees of the company, including Drs. Belanoff and Fishman and Messrs. Robb and Maduck, in recognition of their accomplishments described above.&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">13</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU16"></a><font style="font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Equity Awards</font><font style="font-style:normal;">.&#160;In February 2017, the Board approved grants of op</font><font style="font-style:normal;">tions to each of our named executive officers.&#160;These option awards vest monthly over a four-year period, subject to the named executive officer&#8217;s continued employment through each applicable vesting date.&nbsp;&nbsp;These awards were given to our named executive off</font><font style="font-style:normal;">icers as an incentive toward their continued service to Corcept, and their work toward achieving our long-term goals. </font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Strong Stockholder Support for our Compensation Decisions</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">At our annual stockholder meeting in 2017, of those stockholders that voted, 95 percent voted to approve the 2016 compensation of our named executive officers and 58 percent voted in favor of our practice of submitting the compensation of our named executive officers to a non-binding stockholder vote once every three years.&nbsp;&nbsp;In light of this support, the Compensation Committee did not change the design of our compensation programs during 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;<font style="Background-color:#FFFFFF;color:#000000;">The Compensation Committee will continue to work to ensure that management&#8217;s interests are aligned with our stockholders&#8217; interests to support long-term value creation. Taking into account the stockholder vote in favor of having a non-binding stockholder vote on executive compensation once every three years, we plan to hold our next advisory vote to approve our named executive officers&#8217; compensation at our 2020 annual stockholder meeting.</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Compensation Principles and Objectives</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Our compensation program is meant to attract, motivate and retain highly qualified executive officers by paying them competitively, consistent with our success and their contributions to it. We set goals designed to link each named executive officer&#8217;s compensation to our corporate performance, such as the attainment of significant research, development, commercial, operational and financial targets.&nbsp;&nbsp;Because pharmaceutical product development can take many years, a portion of our executives&#8217; compensation is determined by achievements that increase stockholder value in the long term.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Except for their salaries, compensation for our named executive officers is performance-based. The Compensation Committee determines the structure and amount of performance-based compensation based on the its members&#8217; knowledge of the most effective practices in the biotechnology and specialty pharmaceutical industries.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">These are the Compensation Committee&#8217;s objectives:</p>
<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</p></td>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">&#x2022;</font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;">Align executive and stockholder interests in both the short and long term by providing equity awards and bonuses that are tied to company and individual performance;</font></p></td></tr></table></div>
<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</p></td>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">&#x2022;</font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;">Make sure compensation is competitive by relying on the Compensation Committee members&#8217; deep expertise and many years&#8217; experience with companies both inside and outside the pharmaceutical industry, recognizing that because of our business model, there may be few directly comparable companies; and</font></p></td></tr></table></div>
<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</p></td>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">&#x2022;</font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;">Recognize that optimum compensation practices for a company with relatively few employees may be substantially different than those for a larger, more mature company.</font></p></td></tr></table></div>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">To realize its objectives, the Compensation Committee has offered our executives stock option grants that reward significant, sustained increases in our stock market value and discretionary bonuses based on the achievement of important corporate goals. The Compensation Committee reviews our performance-based compensation offerings at least annually.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The Chairman of the Board and the members of the Compensation Committee are seasoned executives of, consultants to, or venture capitalists with investments in, the biotechnology and specialty pharmaceutical industry.&#160;Collectively they have served as board and compensation committee members of many public and privately held companies including NuGen, Jazz Pharmaceuticals, Aimune Therapeutics, Symantec, Sunesis Pharmaceuticals, Adamas Pharmaceuticals, Intercept Pharmaceuticals, Geron Corporation and Cerus Corporation.&#160;As a result of this extensive involvement in the compensation of executives in these and other companies, we believe that the Chairman of the Board and the members of the Compensation Committee clearly understand the compensation structures and amounts that are necessary to attract, motivate and retain management talent in our industry.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">14</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU17"></a><font style="font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Determination of Compensation</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The Compensation Committee reviews the performance of our named executive officers annually. To aid the Compensation Committee in its deliberations, our Chief Executive Officer reviews the performance of all executives other than himself and makes compensation recommendations regarding them.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Compensation Committee bases its review on the Chief Executive Officer&#8217;s input and on its evaluation of the achievements of Corcept and of each executive during the period.&#160;The Compensation Committee then sets salaries, performance bonuses and grants of stock options, taking into account its members&#8217; understanding of compensation practices in the biotechnology and pharmaceutical industry and the members&#8217; experiences as executives, consultants, board and compensation committee members, and investors in such companies.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Tax Considerations</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">In making its compensation determinations, our Compensation Committee considers the impact of Section 162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended, which limits the tax deductibility by us of annual compensation in excess of $1,000,000 paid to our named executive officers.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">While the tax impact of any compensation arrangement is one factor to be considered, such impact is evaluated in light of the Compensation Committee&#8217;s overall compensation philosophy and objectives. The Compensation Committee considers ways to maximize the deductibility of executive compensation, while retaining the flexibility to compensate officers in a manner commensurate with their performance and the competitive market for executive talent. The Compensation Committee may award compensation to our named executive officers that may not be fully deductible if it determines that such compensation is in our stockholders&#8217; best interests and is consistent with our compensation principles.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Elements of Executive Compensation</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Base Compensation</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The Compensation Committee determines our executives&#8217; salaries based on its members&#8217; many years of assessing competitive market rates and the salaries required to attract, motivate and retain talented executives.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each year the Compensation Committee reviews the Chief Executive Officer&#8217;s salary to determine if a change is appropriate based on its assessment of market trends and our company&#8217;s commercial and clinical performance. The Compensation Committee applies similar scrutiny to the salaries of our other officers, with input from the Chief Executive Officer. No formulaic salary increases are provided to our named executive officers. The Compensation Committee increased the annual base salary for Drs. Belanoff and Fishman and Messrs. Robb and Maduck each by 5.5 percent, effective March 1, 2017, to reflect its assessment of market trends for cost of living increases.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Performance-Based Compensation</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Cash Bonus.<font style="font-style:normal;"> We pay discretionary bonuses annually based on the Compensation Committee&#8217;s assessment of our company&#8217;s and each named executive officer&#8217;s contribution to the achievement of significant corporate goals. The Compensation Committee believes that the best way to ensure that our executives&#8217; compensation is aligned with our business objectives and the interests of our stockholders is to retain the discretion to pay bonuses when significant goals are met, such as the approval of a new product, a significant increase in revenue, substantial advances to our research and development programs, and building our management and operational capabilities. The achievement of these types of milestones does not necessarily correspond with annual performance periods.&nbsp;&nbsp;Performance-based cash compensation has been awarded in recent years primarily to recognize the accomplishment of such value-enhancing goals, substantial revenue growth and achievement of important pre-clinical and clinical goals.</font></p>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">15</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU18"></a><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">In February 2018, the Compensation Committee evaluated the performance of our company and each of our named executive officers with respect to our short- and long-term </font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">goals.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Compensation Committee reviewed the accomplishments set forth in the Executive Summary above, including significant growth in our revenue and cash balance, the advancement of relacorilant to treat patients with hypercortisolism and solid tumors</font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">, the start of clinical trials of CORT125281 to treat patients with CRPC and CORT118335 to treat patients with serious metabolic disorders. and the pre-clinical development of additional selective cortisol modulators.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Compensation Committee approved b</font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">onus payments in the following amounts: Dr. Belanoff: $702,000; Mr. Maduck: $320,000; Mr. Robb: $320,000; and Dr. Fishman: $171,672.</font><font style="Background-color:#FFFFFF;color:#000000;"> </font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Long-Term Equity Incentive Program. <font style="font-style:normal;">All of our employees, including our named executive officers, are eligible to receive grants of stock options under our 2012 Incentive Award Plan. We believe that equity ownership is necessary to link executive compensation to the performance of our stock and our sustained growth. We have used stock options as our long-term performance-based equity incentive vehicle, because the Compensation Committee believes that stock options maximize an executive&#8217;s incentive to increase stockholder value, since there is no financial gain to an executive officer unless our stock price appreciates.</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The Compensation Committee typically grants stock options upon a named executive officer joining our company and once per year in connection with its determination of the named executive officer&#8217;s potential future performance.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Compensation Committee also typically grants stock options following a significant change in job responsibility or in recognition of a significant achievement.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Compensation Committee determines the number of shares underlying each stock option grant based on a number of factors, including the executive officer&#8217;s salary, such executive officer&#8217;s contributions to the achievement of our financial and strategic objectives, the value of the stock option at the time of grant, the possible value of the option if we achieve our objectives, and the Compensation Committee&#8217;s understanding of industry practices and norms. The relative weight given to each of these factors is at the Compensation Committee&#8217;s discretion. There is no set formula. </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">To maximize the incentive for continued employment, stock options granted to our named executive officers generally have a four-year vesting schedule, measured from the date of grant.&#160;We have occasionally granted stock options that vest based on the attainment of performance goals. Stock option awards generally expire ten years from the date of the grant, which allows the executive to focus on the creation and sustainment of long-term stockholder value and to have a reasonable opportunity to benefit from price appreciation in our shares. The exercise price of such stock options is 100% of the fair market value of our stock on the date of grant. </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">In February 2017, the Board approved grants of options to our named executive officers to purchase shares of our common stock: 550,000 shares to Dr. Belanoff; 400,000 shares to Mr. Maduck; 200,000 shares to Mr. Robb; and 100,000 shares to Dr. Fishman.&#160;These stock option awards vest in substantially equal monthly installments over a four-year period from the grant date, subject to the named executive officer&#8217;s continued employment through each applicable vesting date. These awards were granted to our named executive officers as an incentive toward their continued service to the company and to further align their interests with the interests of our stockholders. The size of each award was based on the Compensation Committee&#8217;s and Board&#8217;s determination of the recipient&#8217;s ability to contribute to our future success.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Severance and Change in Control Arrangements</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">We entered into Severance and Change in Control Agreements with each of our named executive officers to encourage continued attention and dedication to duties without distraction should there arise the possibility of an change in control of our company and to help ensure a smooth transition should such a change in control occur.&nbsp;&nbsp;The terms of the agreements are identical.&#160;For a detailed description of the Severance and Change in Control Agreements, see <font style="font-style:italic;">&#8220;Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control &#8211; Severance and Change in Control Agreements&#8221;</font> below.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">16</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU19"></a><font style="font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Other Elements of Compensation</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Our executives are eligible to receive the following retirement and insurance benefits on the same terms as our other employees.<font style="font-style:italic;">&nbsp;&nbsp;</font>Eligibility for all employees begins on the first day of the month coinciding with or immediately following the first business day of employment.&nbsp;&nbsp;These benefits help us attract and retain talented employees in a competitive employment market, where such benefits are common.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each year, we review the benefits package we offer.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">401(k) Plan.<font style="font-style:normal;"> We have a Section 401(k) Savings/Retirement Plan, or 401(k) Plan, to cover eligible employees of the company and any designated affiliate. The 401(k) Plan permits eligible employees to defer up to 100% of their annual compensation, subject to limitations imposed by the Internal Revenue Code.&nbsp;&nbsp;All contributions are immediately vested and non-forfeitable. We make no matching contributions</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Medical Insurance.<font style="font-style:normal;">&#160;At our sole cost, we provide each eligible employee and his or her spouse and children with health, dental and vision insurance.</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Life and Disability Insurance.<font style="font-style:normal;"> At our sole cost, we provide each eligible employee disability and life insurance.</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Policies with Respect to Equity Compensation Awards</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">We grant all stock option awards based on the fair market value as of the date of grant.&#160;We do not have a policy of granting stock option awards at other than the fair market value of our common stock.&#160;The exercise price for each stock option grant is based on the last quoted price per share on the Nasdaq Capital Market on the date of grant.&#160;We do not have a policy and do not intend to have a policy or practice to select option grant dates for named executive officers in coordination with the release of material non-public information.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">We also have an insider trading policy that prohibits our named executive officers and Board members from engaging in short-term or speculative transactions in our stock, including short sales.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Summary Compensation Table</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The following table provides compensation information for the years ended December 31, 2017, 2016 and 2015 for each of our named executive officers.</p>

<p style="text-align:right;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">647,333</p></td>
<td valign="bottom"  BGCOLOR="#CFF0FC" style="padding-left:0pt;padding-Right:0.75pt;padding-Top:0.75pt;padding-Bottom:0pt;width:1%;white-space:nowrap;">
<p style="margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">&nbsp;</p></td>
<td valign="bottom"  BGCOLOR="#CFF0FC" style="padding-left:0pt;padding-Right:0.75pt;padding-Top:0.75pt;padding-Bottom:0pt;width:1%;">
<p style="text-align:right;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">&nbsp;</p></td>

<td valign="top" style="width:2.99%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><sup style="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</sup></font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8pt;"><a name="_Hlk511985276"></a><a name="_Hlk511985276"></a>Bonus amounts for 2015 and 2016 were previously reported based on the year paid and have been updated to reflect the year to which the bonus paid principally related.</p></td></tr></table></div>

<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:2.99%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><sup style="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(2)</sup></font></p></td>
<td valign="top">

Amounts reported constitute the grant date fair value of option awards as calculated under FASB ASC To</font><font style="font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">pic 718. The relevant assumptions used to calculate the value of the option awards are set forth in Part IV &#8211; Item 15(1) - Financial Statements, Notes to Financial Statements, Note 8 &#8211; &#8220;Preferred Stock and Stockholders&#8217; Equity &#8211; Stock-Based Compensation Re</font><font style="font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">lated to Employee and Director Options&#8221; in our Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2017.</font></p></td></tr></table></div>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:2.99%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><sup style="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</sup></font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8pt;">Each unvested option vests and becomes exercisable in substantially equal monthly installments through the fourth anniversary of the vesting commencement date, subject to the named executive officer&#8217;s continued services through the applicable vesting date.</p></td></tr></table></div>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Option Exercises in 2017</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The following table includes certain information with regard to options exercised by our named executive officers during 2017.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</p>
<div>
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="center" style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="bottom"  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" style="padding-left:0pt;padding-Right:0.75pt;padding-Top:0.75pt;padding-Bottom:0pt;width:32.12%;">

<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:2.99%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><sup style="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</sup></font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8pt;">The value realized on the exercise represents the excess of the closing price of our common stock on the date of exercise over the exercise price of the shares.</p></td></tr></table></div>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">19</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU22"></a><font style="font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Pension Benefits</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">None of our named executive officers participate in or have account balances in qualified or non-qualified defined benefit plans sponsored by us.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Nonqualified Deferred Compensation</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">None of our named executives participate in or have account balances in non-qualified defined contribution plans or other deferred compensation plans maintained by us.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:7.69%;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Severance and Change in Control Agreements</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">We have entered into Severance and Change in Control Agreements with each of our named executive officers. The terms of the agreements are identical. The agreements provide that, if the executive&#8217;s employment is terminated by us without &#8220;cause&#8221; or by the executive for &#8220;good reason&#8221; (as each term is defined in the agreements) prior to or more than 18 months following a change in control, the executive will be eligible to receive 12 months of his or her then-current base salary, payable in substantially equal installments in accordance with the company&#8217;s customary payroll procedures and continued health insurance coverage for up to 12 months following the date of termination. In addition, the agreements provide that in the event the executive&#8217;s employment is terminated by us without &#8220;cause&#8221; or by the executive for &#8220;good reason&#8221; within 18 months following a change in control, the executive will be eligible to receive an amount equal to 12 months of his or her then-current base salary payable in a lump sum, continued health insurance coverage for up to 12 months following the date of termination, and full vesting of all outstanding equity awards. The receipt of any severance will be subject to the executive signing and not revoking a separation agreement and release of claims in a form reasonably acceptable to us within 60 days following executive&#8217;s termination of employment. No severance will be paid or provided until the separation agreement and release of claims becomes effective.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">20</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU23"></a><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The following table reflects compensation payab</font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">le to each of Drs. Belanoff and Fishman and Messrs. Robb and Maduck upon a change in control or various employment termination events.&#160;The amounts shown below assume that (i) the named executive officer experienced a qualifying termination effective as of </font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">December 31, 2017 or (ii) a change in control of our company occurred and the named executive officer experienced a qualifying termination on December 31, 2017.</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Termination</p>

<p style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Following a</p>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Change in Control</p></td>

<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:2.99%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><sup style="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</sup></font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8pt;">For unvested options held by named executive officers as of December 31, 2017, the value ascribed to the change in control acceleration features under the Severance and Change in Control Agreements is calculated by multiplying any excess in the closing price for our company&#8217;s common stock on the Nasdaq Stock Market as of December 29, 2017, $18.06, over the exercise price of the option grant, times the number of unvested shares in the option grant as of that date.</p></td></tr></table></div>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Risk Assessment of Compensation Programs</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Our Compensation Committee and Board have determined that our compensation policies, plans and practices are appropriately balanced and do not create risks that will have a material adverse effect on our company.&#160;To make this determination, they reviewed the company&#8217;s compensation policies, plans and practices with a focus on compensation program design, payment methodology, relationship to performance and length of performance period, and oversight and controls as compared to the compensation practices that they have seen in similar companies. During the review, the Compensation Committee noted risk mitigating factors inherent in our compensation practices, including the Compensation Committee&#8217;s and management&#8217;s discretion in approving executive and employee compensation and establishing performance goals for short and long-term compensation plans, the balance between fixed and variable pay and the mix of short and long-term incentives that encourage consistent performance over a sustained period, and these factors aligned the interests of our named executive officers and employees with those of our stockholders.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">21</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU24"></a><a name="EQUITY_COMPENSATION_PLAN_INFORMATION"></a><font style="font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="EQUITY_COMPENSATION_PLAN_INFORMATION"></a>EQUITY COMPENSATIO</font><font style="font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">N PLAN INFORMATION</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The following table provides information as of December 31, 2017 with respect to the shares of our common stock that may be issued under all of our existing equity compensation plans, which consist of the 2012 Incentive Award Plan and the 2004 Equity Incentive Plan.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</p>

<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8pt;">The 2012 Incentive Award Plan contains an &#8220;evergreen&#8221; provision that allows for increases on the first day of each year beginning in 2013 and ending in 2022, the lesser of an additional (i)&#160;8,000,000 shares of our common stock, (ii)&#160;4% of the outstanding shares of common stock on the immediately preceding December&#160;31 or (iii)&#160;such smaller number of shares determined by the Board. None of our other plans has an &#8220;evergreen&#8221; provision. On February 7, 2018, the Board authorized an &#8220;evergreen&#8221; increase in the shares available for grant under the 2012 Plan to be equivalent to 4% of the shares of our common stock outstanding on December 31, 2017, which represented an increase of 4,588,682 shares to the plan.</p></td></tr></table></div>

<td valign="top" style="width:2.99%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><sup style="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</sup></font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8pt;">Amounts shown do not reflect compensation actually received by the directors or the actual value that may be recognized by the directors with respect to these awards in the future. Instead, the amounts shown represent the grant date fair value of the awards as calculated under FASB ASC Topic 718. The relevant assumptions used to calculate the value of the option awards are set forth in Part IV &#8211; Item 15(1) - Financial Statements, Notes to Financial Statements, Note 8 &#8211; &#8220;Preferred Stock and Stockholders&#8217; Equity &#8211; Stock-Based Compensation Related to Employee and Director Options&#8221; in our Annual Report on Form&#160;10-K for the year ended December 31, 2017.</p></td></tr></table></div>
<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:2.99%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-size:8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><sup style="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(2)</sup></font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:8pt;">As of December 31, 2017, our non-employee directors held options outstanding to purchase the following number of shares: Mr.&#160;Baker: 300,000; Mr.&#160;Bradbury:&#160;220,000; Mr. Swisher: 150,000; Mr.&#160;Mahoney:&#160;310,000; Ms.&#160;<font style="color:#000000;">Gal&#225;</font>:&#160;100,000 shares; and Mr. Wilson: 1,340,000 shares. During 2017, Mr. Wilson, as chairman of the board, was granted an option to purchase 90,000 shares with a grant date fair value of $698,575, Messrs. Baker, Bradbury, Swisher, Mahoney and Ms. <font style="color:#000000;">Gal&#225;</font> were each granted an option to purchase 30,000 shares with a grant date fair value of $232,858.&#160;All of these awards vest pro-rata over a one-year period at the rate of 8.3334% on the monthly anniversary of the date of grant, subject to continued service.</p></td></tr></table></div>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">22</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU25"></a><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">For 2017, non-employee directors received a director fee from us for their services as members of the Board in the amount of $40,000 per year. In addition, the Chair and members of the Audit Committee received fees of $20,000 and $10,000, respectively, per</font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"> year; the Chair and members of the Compensation Committee received fees of $15,000 and $7,000, respectively, per year; the Chair and members of the Corporate Governance &amp; Nominating Committee received fees of $10,000 and $5,000, respectively, per year.&nbsp;&nbsp;C</font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">ommencing February 1, 2017, the chairman of our board of directors received an annual cash retainer of $120,000 in lieu of any other fees.&nbsp;&nbsp;New directors are granted an option to purchase 60,000 shares of our common stock in connection with their initial e</font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">lection to the Board. The initial director options vest with respect to 25% of the shares on the first anniversary of the date of the grant and, thereafter, at the rate of 2.08334% per month, until fully vested, subject to the director&#8217;s continued service.</font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">&nbsp;&nbsp;Non-employee directors who are reelected at the Annual Meeting are each granted an option to purchase 30,000 shares of our common stock that vests over one year at the rate of 8.3334% per month from the date of the Annual Meeting until fully vested, subj</font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">ect to the director&#8217;s continued service. The Board has also historically approved larger option awards for directors serving certain leadership roles.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2017, the Board approved an option covering 90,000 shares of our common stock to Mr. Wilson for his s</font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">ervice as Chairman of the Board. </font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">We have entered into a Severance and Change in Control Agreement with James N. Wilson, Chairman of the Board. The agreement with Mr. Wilson provides that if his employment or service on the Board is terminated involuntarily by us without &#8220;cause&#8221; or by him for &#8220;good reason&#8221; (as each is defined in the agreement) within 18 months following a change in control all of his outstanding equity awards shall become fully vested. Mr. Wilson will only receive vesting acceleration under this agreement if he signs and does not revoke a separation agreement and release of claims in a form reasonably acceptable to our Company within 60 days following termination of employment. No vesting acceleration will be provided to Mr. Wilson until the separation agreement and release of claims becomes effective.</p>
<p style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Pay Ratio Disclosure</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act and Regulation S-K require us to report the ratio of the <font style="font-style:italic;">median</font> annual compensation of our full- and part-time employees in 2017 (that is, the employee whose compensation is in the middle of the group, with as many employees earning more as earned less, not including our CEO) to the annual total compensation of our CEO. </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">We identified the employee with median compensation by comparing the W-2 gross income (Box 1) of all full- and part-time employees (except our CEO) who were employed on December 31, 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;To permit meaningful comparisons between full- and part-time employees and between employees who worked for us less than the entire year, we annualized each employee&#8217;s compensation based on the percentage of the year they worked for us. The annual total compensation of our median employee was $297,689 for 2017, including the grant date fair value options granted that year and the bonus paid in February 2018 based on 2017 performance.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">As disclosed above in the Summary Compensation Table, our CEO&#8217;s annual total compensation for 2017 was $4,271,452.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">As calculated above, the annual total compensation of our median employee excluding the CEO to that of our CEO is as follows:</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:5.13%;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">$</p></td>

<p style="margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;color:#000000;font-size:1pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">&nbsp;</p></td>

<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Because public companies use different methods to calculate their pay ratios, the ratio we report should not be used as a basis for comparing Corcept to its peers.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">23</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU26"></a><a name="COMPENSATION_COMMITTEE_REPORT"></a><font style="font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="COMPENSATION_COMMITTEE_REPORT"></a>COMPENSATION COM</font><font style="font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">MITTEE REPORT*</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The Compensation Committee of the Board, or Compensation Committee, has furnished this report on executive compensation. None of the members of the Compensation Committee is currently our officer or employee and all are &#8220;non-employee directors&#8221; for purposes of Rule 16b-3 under the Exchange Act and &#8220;outside directors&#8221; for purposes of Section 162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code. The Compensation Committee is responsible for designing, recommending to the Board for approval and evaluating our compensation plans, policies and programs and reviewing and approving the compensation of the Chief Executive Officer and other officers and directors.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">This report, filed in accordance with Item 407(e)(5) of Regulation S-K, should be read in conjunction with the other information relating to executive compensation, which is contained elsewhere in this Proxy Statement and is not repeated here.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">In this context, the Compensation Committee hereby reports as follows:</p>
<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">1.</font></p></td>
<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The Compensation Committee has reviewed and discussed the Compensation Discussion and Analysis required by Item 402(b) of Regulation S-K contained herein with management; and</p></td></tr></table></div>
<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"  style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">

<td valign="top">
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Based on the review and discussions referred to in paragraph (1) above, the Compensation Committee recommended to our Board that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in this Proxy Statement and incorporated by reference to our Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2017.</p></td></tr></table></div>

<p style="text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">24</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;">
<p style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU27"></a><a name="REPORT__AUDIT_COMMITTEE"></a><font style="font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="REPORT__AUDIT_COMMITTEE"></a>REPORT OF THE AU</font><font style="font-weight:bold;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">DIT COMMITTEE*</font></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Under the guidance of a written charter adopted by the Board, the purpose of the Audit Committee is to oversee the accounting and financial reporting processes of the Company and audits of its financial statements. The responsibilities of the Audit Committee include appointing and providing for the compensation of the Company&#8217;s independent registered public accounting firm. Each of the members of the Audit Committee meets the independence requirements of NASDAQ and the SEC. </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Management has primary responsibility for the system of internal controls and the financial reporting process. The independent registered public accounting firm has the responsibility to express an opinion on the financial statements and internal control over financial reporting based on an audit conducted in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB). </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">In this context and in connection with the audited financial statements contained in the Company&#8217;s Annual Report on Form&#160;10-K, the Audit Committee: </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:7.69%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">The Audit Committee has also recommended, subject to stockholder ratification in Proposal 2 in this Proxy Statement, the appointment of Ernst &amp; Young LLP as the Company&#8217;s independent registered public accounting firm for the fiscal year ending December 31, 2018.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:11pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:64.1%;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">AUDIT COMMITTEE</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-top:11pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:64.1%;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Daniel N. Swisher, Jr., Chairman</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:64.1%;text-indent:0%;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Rene&#233; D. Gal&#225;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:64.1%;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">David L. Mahoney</p>
<div align="left">
